icitly, higher-level testing is needed. Assuming parameter-based design, Unit is minimum but Integration probability is elevated due to timezone library integration concerns.","test_description":"Unit tests using the actual timezone library (dateutil.tz or zoneinfo) with explicit timezone objects. Define a schedule for 2:30 AM in a DST-observing timezone (e.g., US/Eastern). Test across spring forward date (2024-03-10 at 2:00 AM → 3:00 AM): verify next run at 2:30 AM correctly yields 3:30 AM or skips depending on policy. Test across fall back date (2024-11-03 at 2:00 AM → 1:00 AM): verify handling of ambiguous 1:30 AM (which occurs twice). Example: schedule_time=02:30 America/New_York, start=2024-03-09 23:00 → next_run=2024-03-10 03:30 (spring forward gap).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a scheduled job's computed next run time has already passed (e.g., system was down), the engine determines whether to skip or backfill based on the job's configured missed-run policy.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The core failure is incorrect policy logic: determining whether to skip or backfill missed runs given (scheduled_time, current_time, policy). This is a pure decision function testable at Unit level. Secondary failure (policy applied in wrong place in scheduler loop) is Integration-level. The logic error is the primary real failure.","test_description":"Parameterized unit tests with (scheduled_time, current_time, missed_run_policy) → expected_action. Test cases: (a) no missed runs (scheduled_time <= current_time by < 1 period), (b) exactly 1 missed run, (c) multiple consecutive missed runs (e.g., job down for 2 days with hourly schedule = ~48 missed). For each, test all policies (skip, backfill_one, backfill_all). Example: scheduled=2PM, current=2:30PM, policy=skip → skip_run; scheduled=2PM, current=2:30PM, policy=backfill_one → queue 